    "quirks": [
      "`results` is keyed by `toptier_agency`, `subtier_agency`, and `office` arrays rather than a single list of match objects.",
      "Search text is case-insensitive but literal; leading/trailing spaces or whitespace-only inputs change which records match.",
      "Limit defaults to 10 per category. Numeric strings and floats are coerced, negative integers return 200 with distorted payloads, and `limit: null` triggers a 500 HTML error.",
      "Server ignores unknown body fields like `extra`, and `messages` remained empty across all observed responses."
    ],
    "risks": [
      "Clients expecting the documented array of match objects will break unless they handle the three separate category arrays.",
      "Office entries can contain null codes or names, so downstream consumers must tolerate missing identifiers.",
      "Unvalidated limit values (floats, negatives, null) can cause huge or malformed payloads or a 500 error; callers should constrain inputs to positive integers."
    ],
    "gaps": [
      "No observed responses populated the `messages` array, so it is unclear when guidance or warnings appear.",
      "True maximum result counts per category remain unknown beyond the ~601 office entries observed for broad terms.",
      "Negative limit behavior varies by query (sometimes dropping toptier results), and the exact rules are undocumented."
    ],
